org.jetbrains.jetCheck

Class Generator<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.jetbrains.jetCheck.Generator<T>

  • public class Generator<T>
extends Object
    A generator for objects based on random data from GenerationEnvironment.

    A generator is a function that takes a source of random data (which is GenerationEnvironment) and, using that random data (e.g. by calling more primitive generators and reinterpreting their results), constructs a value of type T. For data structures returning the same data, generators should produce equivalent values.

    Generators for standard types can be obtained using static methods of this class (e.g. integers(), listsOf(org.jetbrains.jetCheck.Generator<T>) etc). Generators for custom types can be created by deriving them from standard types (e.g. via map(java.util.function.Function<? super T, ? extends V>), flatMap(java.util.function.Function<? super T, ? extends org.jetbrains.jetCheck.Generator<V>>), zipWith(org.jetbrains.jetCheck.Generator<A>, org.jetbrains.jetCheck.Generator<B>, java.util.function.BiFunction<? super A, ? super B, ? extends C>)) or by writing your own from scratch (from(Function)).

    • Method Detail

      • from

        @NotNull
public static <T> Generator<T> from(@NotNull
                                              Function<GenerationEnvironment,T> function)
        Creates a generator from a custom function, that creates objects of the given type based on the data from GenerationEnvironment. The generator may invoke other, more primitive, generators using GenerationEnvironment.generate(Generator).

        When a property is falsified, the GenerationEnvironment is attempted to be minimized (shrunk), and the generator will be run on ever "smaller" versions of it.

        To ensure test reproducibility during re-run or shrinking phase, the result of the generators should only depend on the GenerationEnvironment. Generators should not have any side effects or depend on the outside world. Generators may have internal mutable state accessible to other (nested) generators, but that's error-prone, difficult and computationally expensive to shrink. If you still think you need that, please see ImperativeCommand for potentially more convenient way of testing stateful systems.

      • noShrink

        public Generator<T> noShrink()
        Turns off automatic shrinking for the data produced by this generator (and its components, if any). This can be useful to speed up shrinking by not wasting time on shrinking objects where it makes no sense. It's especially useful when using stateful generators (e.g. ImperativeCommand), because shrinkable values there can lead to doubling of the shrinking time.

      • suchThat

        public Generator<T> suchThat(@NotNull
                             Predicate<? super T> condition)
        Attempts to generate the value several times, until one comes out that satisfies the given condition. That value is returned as generator result. Results of all previous attempts are discarded. During shrinking, the underlying data structures from those attempts won't be used for re-running generation, so be careful that those attempts don't leave any traces of themselves (e.g. side effects, even ones internal to an outer generator).

        If the condition still fails after a large number of attempts, data generation is stopped prematurely and CannotSatisfyCondition exception is thrown.

        This method is useful to avoid infrequent corner cases (e.g. integers().suchThat(i -> i != 0)). To eliminate large portions of search space, this strategy might prove ineffective and result in generator failure due to inability to come up with satisfying examples (e.g. integers().suchThat(i -> i > 0 && i <= 10) where the condition would be true in just 10 of about 4 billion times). In such cases, please consider changing the generator instead of using suchThat.

      • recursive

        @NotNull
public static <T> Generator<T> recursive(@NotNull
                                                   Function<? super Generator<T>,? extends Generator<T>> createGenerator)
        A fixed-point combinator to easily create recursive generators by giving a name to the whole generator and allowing to reuse it inside itself. For example, a recursive tree generator could be defined as follows by binding itself to the name nodes: 
         Generator<Node> gen = Generator.recursive(nodes -> Generator.anyOf(
   Generator.constant(new Leaf()),
   Generator.listsOf(nodes).map(children -> new Composite(children))))
        Returns:
        the generator returned from the passed function
